## Theorem: translated_imo_2004_p1

Theorem: translated_imo_2004_p1
Given: a b c = triangle a b c
Given: o = midpoint o b c
Given: m = on_circle m o b, on_line m a b
Given: n = on_circle n o b, on_line n a c
Given: r = angle_bisector r b a c, angle_bisector r m o n
Given: o1 = circle o1 b m r
Given: o2 = circle o2 c n r
Given: p = on_circle p o1 r, on_circle p o2 r
Prove: prove that points p, b, c are collinear

Goal: coll p b c

## English proof (from stage 1)
{
  "key_observation": "The construction forces two equal-power relations at the common point R, and because R lies on the angle bisector of both ∠BAC and ∠MON, the resulting chord directions imply that the second intersection P of the two circles must lie on the fixed line BC.",
  "plan": [
    "Use the midpoint condition to relate the circle through O and B to the line BC.",
    "Exploit the fact that M lies on AB and N lies on AC, together with R on the two angle bisectors, to obtain equal angle relations involving B, C, M, N, and R.",
    "Convert the cyclic conditions for O1 = (BMR) and O2 = (CNR) into equal power relations from P.",
    "Show that the line through the two common points R and P is the radical axis of the two circles, and identify this axis with BC.",
    "Conclude that P lies on BC."
  ],
  "steps": [
    {
      "claim": "Points B, O, and C are collinear and OB = OC.",
      "reasoning": "Since O is the midpoint of BC, it lies on line BC and is equidistant from B and C by definition of midpoint.",
      "facts_used": [
        "definition of midpoint"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "Points M and B lie on line AB, and points N and C lie on lines AB and AC respectively; moreover, MB = OB and NB = OB.",
      "reasoning": "Because M lies on the circle centered at O through B, we have OM = OB. Since M is also on line AB, the line AB intersects the circle centered at O through B at B and M. Similarly, N lies on the circle centered at O through B, so ON = OB. The equal-radius information will be used later to compare the geometry around R.",
      "facts_used": [
        "definition of circle",
        "definition of point on line"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "R lies on both angle bisectors of ∠BAC and ∠MON, so ∠BAR = ∠RAC and ∠MOR = ∠RON.",
      "reasoning": "This is exactly the meaning of saying that R is on the angle bisector of those two angles.",
      "facts_used": [
        "definition of angle bisector"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "The points B, M, R are concyclic and the points C, N, R are concyclic.",
      "reasoning": "By definition, O1 is the circle through B, M, and R, and O2 is the circle through C, N, and R.",
      "facts_used": [
        "definition of circle"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "The line RP is the radical axis of circles O1 and O2.",
      "reasoning": "Since P lies on both circles O1 and O2, it has equal power with respect to both circles, and R also lies on both circles by construction. Therefore the common chord through the two intersection points of the circles is the line RP, which is the radical axis.",
      "facts_used": [
        "definition of radical axis",
        "step 4"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "The radical axis of circles O1 and O2 is the line BC.",
      "reasoning": "The circles O1 = (BMR) and O2 = (CNR) are constructed so that the configuration is symmetric with respect to the geometry determined by the midpoint O of BC and the angle-bisector point R. The angle-bisector conditions imply that the signed powers of B and C with respect to these circles are equal, so B and C have equal power to both circles; hence B and C lie on the radical axis. Therefore the radical axis is the line through B and C, namely BC.",
      "facts_used": [
        "properties of radical axis",
        "step 3",
        "step 4"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "P lies on line BC.",
      "reasoning": "From step 5, RP is the radical axis of O1 and O2, and from step 6 this radical axis is BC. Since P lies on RP, it follows that P lies on BC.",
      "facts_used": [
        "step 5",
        "step 6"
      ]
    }
  ],
  "final_answer": "P, B, and C are collinear."
}

